headline: Profit slide at Target hints at meager holiday season for the retailer

headline: Target plans another $1 billion investment to jumpstart sales
summary:
STORY: Shares of Target opened lower on Wednesday after the big-box retailer reported a bigger-than-expected drop in same-store sales.

Target has now reported five straight quarters of sales declines. 

The results come as still-high inflation and tariff worries have forced many U.S. consumers to pull back on spending.

Target said it would invest about $1 billion in new stores, remodels and its digital business next year as part of a turnaround plan.

Target named longtime executive Michael Fiddelke as its new CEO in August to steer the business back to health.

Fiddelke, who takes over early next year, has already slashed 1,800 corporate roles in order to reduce costs and streamline operations.

Shares of Target have lost more than a third of their value this year, hurt by negative comparable sales and market share losses to bigger rival Walmart, which reports its third-quarter earnings on Thursday.
